Excellent essay, relevant in the current Q* discussion, by 
@finbarrtimbers
 (ex DeepMind)

"Greedy sampling is the worst form of sampling, except all those other forms that have been tried from time to time." - Winston Churchill, if he worked in NLP"

https://artfintel.com/p/why-do-llms-use-greedy-sampling (h/t 
@johannes_hage
)

- Greedy sampling in LLMs is surprisingly effective despite its simplicity. Contrary to complex search methods in RL (e.g., MCTS in AlphaZero), greedy sampling balances computational efficiency with quality output in language tasks

- Advanced search methods (like beam search) often don't scale well with language models, leading to less diverse or even degenerate text outputs. Greedy sampling, while basic, avoids these pitfalls, offering a pragmatic approach.

"In short, search can be viewed as one possible answer to the “conditional compute” problem. Another answer is MoE, particularly with Expert Choice routing, and MoE is much better suited to the current computational paradigm of running these models in a model/tensor-parallel way on massive supercomputers. And because we have an excellent baseline technique that works to soak up excess compute— increasing model size— search has a high bar to overcome that. Current techniques haven’t."
